<DOC><DOCNO> AP890710-0244 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-89 0654EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     07-10 0876</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0913</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's unemployment rate climbed 0.1percentage point to 5.3 percent in June as continued declines inmanufacturing and construction slowed overall job growth, thegovernment said.   Analysts were split on whether the jobless data provided Fridayby the Labor Department suggested a recession was nearing, but theywere unanimous in saying there was nothing in the report to changethe Federal Reserve's apparent decision to ease monetary policy.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Reserve, faced with further signsof a weakening economy, launched a second round of credit easingthis past week even before the end of a crucial midyear review ofmonetary policy, private economists said.   The analysts predicted Friday that the move would send a varietyof consumer and business interest rates lower, with one saying thata cut in commercial banks' prime lending rate could come as early asMonday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Americans took out $3.6 billion more inconsumer debt than they retired in May as the pace of borrowingturned upward again, the government reported.   The Federal Reserve Board said Friday that consumer credit in Mayrose at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.2 percent, up fromthe 4.3 percent pace of April.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Time Inc. said it had received financingcommitments from 40 banks for its $14 billion tender offer forWarner Communications Inc.   Time, which is pursuing a merger with Warner and trying to fendoff an unwanted $12.2 billion bid from Paramount CommunicationsInc., said Friday the banks offered to provide a total of $27.5billion in financing. The media giant has said it needs $8.35billion to complete the cash portion of its offer for Warner.   The announcement came as lawyers prepared for a hearing inDelaware Chancery Court on Tuesday that could determine the outcomeof the three-way struggle for Time.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government rested its case in the firstsecurities racketeering trial after playing a tape of a formerDrexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader telling a Princeton-NewportPartners LP executive after an alleged illegal deal: ``Welcome tothe world of being a sleaze.''   Also, defense lawyers declined Friday to cross-examine DrexelChief Executive Frederick H. Joseph for fear of introducing intoevidence potentially damaging information about Drexel's $650million plea deal with the government.   The ``sleaze'' tape was one of 14 conversations played by federalprosecutors at the closely watched Wall Street fraud trial of fivepartners in Princeton-Newport, a defunct brokerage, and ex-Drexeltrader Bruce Lee Newberg.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government announced a stricter policy todeal with threats against aviation, including a system that requiresairlines to take countermeasures and imposes fines for disclosingsecurity alerts.   A Federal Aviation Administration order, which will go intoeffect Monday, replaces the current system of issuing securitybulletins, criticized after the bombing of a Pan Am flight overScotland last December that killed 270 people.   Under the new order disclosed Friday, individuals or airlinesthat disclose information from government security alerts withoutFAA authorization will be fined _ up to $1,000 for individuals and$10,000 for airlines.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Members of ATandamp;T's two unions haveoverwhelmingly ratified new 3-year contracts providing them with thecompany's first profit-sharing plan for union workers and a packageof family-related benefits, the unions said.   The Communications Workers of America and the InternationalBrotherhood of Electrical Workers did not provide a breakdown of thesecret-ballot ratification vote but said Friday it was approved by``huge margins'' in every bargaining unit nationwide.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Food and Drug Administration said it isbanning sales of non-prescription antibaldness creams andaphrodisiac products because none has been shown to work.   Over-the-counter hair-growth products _ usually sold by mail orthrough barbers or beauticians _ have dwindled in number since theFDA indicated in 1985 that it would ban the products.   But the FDA said Friday these products ``have continued to be anarea of considerable fraud. The ban of all such products willprovide a greater and more uniform protection to the public.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Labor Department proposed nearly $2 millionin fines against a Ford Motor Co. subsidiary it said had repeatedlyviolated an agreement reached with the automaker two years ago byfailing to adequately report injuries and illnesses.   The subsidiary, Ford Electronics and Refrigeration Corp. ofLansdale, Pa., was given 15 working days to contest the fineproposed by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, thegovernment said Friday.   Ford officials did not immediately return telephone calls seekingcomment.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market advanced broadly Friday, as the Dow Jonesaverage of 30 industrials climbed 25.42 points to 2,487.86,stretching its advance for a holiday-shortened week of fourconsecutive gains to 47.80 points.   Bond prices climbed on more evidence the economy is slowing.   The dollar finished lower against all major currencies except theJapanese yen after a steady selloff sparked by speculation thatinterest rates would decline.   Silver futures prices fell sharply; gold futures settled lower;copper futures made strong gains; coffee futures sank; oil futuresrose; grains and soybeans were lower; and livestock and meat mostlyfell.</TEXT></DOC>